english:
  title: A Defense Against Accusations of Madness
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The world says the hermit is mad. But the hermit is not mad. Perhaps those who call the hermit mad are themselves mad to a greater degree. Have they truly witnessed it? Have they heard it? If they have seen and heard the hermit's so-called madness, what does it amount to? Does he strip naked and wade barefoot through fire and water? Does he gnaw sand and stone until his teeth crack and his lips bleed? Does he shake his fist at heaven and curse the skies? Does he kick the earth and rail against it? Does he let his hair fall loose and wail? Does he run naked through the streets? Does he not feel the winter's cold or summer's heat? Does he chase the wind and grasp at the moon? If such things were so, then yes, he would be mad. But since they are not, how can madness be charged against him?

    Alas, the people of this world! When at leisure in their halls, their bearing and speech are proper, their dress and grooming refined—all appears as it should. Yet the moment they take office and assume public authority, their hands remain two, yet move in ways never seen before; their hearts remain one, yet harbor twisted intentions. Their ears and eyes grow confused, east becomes west, all blurs into deception. They lose the middle path and know not how to return to it. In the end, they lose the reins, stray from the way, and only when they stumble and fall do they cease. This is madness dressed in propriety—a madness dwelling within while correctness shows without. Is not this madness far greater than one who merely wades through fire and gnaws at stone?

    Alas, the world is full of such madness, yet people cannot see their own affliction. Why then do they mock the hermit's madness? The hermit is not mad. His appearance mimics madness, but his heart remains true.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The term 居士 (hermit/scholar-recluse) refers to a learned person who has withdrawn from official service, a common identity for Korean literati.
  - key: ''
    value: This work is a classical satire employing paradox and inversion—what appears mad is sane, what appears sane is mad—to critique the corruption and moral degradation of officials.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Gyeou-bo (1168-1241) was a renowned Goryeo scholar and official who used literature as social commentary.
